<section xml:id="Angles_and_Their_Measure">
  <title>Angles and Their Measure</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      One method people use to identify their position is by looking at the <em>latitude</em>.
          <idx><h>Latitude</h></idx>
      These imaginary lines that form circles around the Earth run parallel to the Equator.
      The latitude of a place is defined as the angle between a line drawn from the center of the earth to that point and the equatorial plane.
      For any point in the Northern Hemisphere,
      a navigator can measure their latitude by determining the angle
      <em>H&#333;k&#363;pa`a</em>
      (North Star) makes with the horizon.
    </p>
    <image>
<latex-image>
<![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}\draw (0,0)--(-0.5,0);
\draw[line width=2pt] (0,0) -- (1.1,0) node[right,xshift=0.1cm] {Horizon};
\draw[line width=2pt] (0,0) -- (30:1.2);
\draw[line width=2pt] (0:0.3cm) arc (0:30:0.3cm) node[midway, right,xshift=0.05cm,yshift=0.1cm] {Angle of H\={o}k\={u}pa`a};
\node [black,scale=1.5] at (30:1.27017059222) {\(\bigstar\)};
\node [yellow] at (30:1.27017059222) {\(\bigstar\)};
\node at (1.4,0.63) {H\={o}k\={u}pa`a};\end{tikzpicture}]]>
</latex-image>
    </image>
    <p>
      When voyaging,
      knowing correct angles can be the difference between finding and missing your destination.
      Navigators pay close attention to angles on the Hawaiian Star Compass to determine where celestial bodies enter and exit the sky as well as where wind and current come from.
      In this section,
      we will examine the properties of angles and their measure.
    </p>
    <definition>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A <term>ray</term>
              <idx><h>Ray</h></idx>
          is a part of a line that begins at a point <m>O</m> and extends in one direction.
        </p>
        <image>
<latex-image>
<![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}\draw[<->] (-5,0) -- (5,0);
\draw[->, line width=2pt,blue,-stealth](0,0) -- (5,0) node[black,midway,below]{Ray};
\node[circle,fill=blue,inner sep=2pt,minimum size=2pt,label=below:{\(O\)}] (a) at (0,0) {};\end{tikzpicture}]]>
</latex-image>
        </image>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <definition>
      <statement>
        <p>
          If two rays have a common vertex, <m>O</m>,
          they form an <term>angle</term>,
              <idx><h>Angle</h></idx>
          <m>\theta</m>.
          The starting ray of the angle is called the <term>initial side</term>
              <idx><h>Initial side</h></idx>
          and the second ray is called the
          <term>terminal side</term>.
              <idx><h>Terminal side</h></idx>
        </p>
        <image>
<latex-image>
<![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}\draw[->, line width=2pt,blue,-stealth](0,0) -- (5,0) node[black,midway,below]{Initial Side};
\draw[->, line width=2pt,blue,-stealth](0,0) -- (40:5) node[black,midway,left,xshift=-0.5cm]{Terminal Side};
\node[circle,fill=blue,inner sep=2pt,minimum size=2pt,label=below:{\(O\)}] (a) at (0,0) {};
\draw[red] ([shift=(0:0.8cm)]0,0) arc (0:40:0.8cm);
\node at (1,0.35) {\(\theta\)};\end{tikzpicture}]]>
</latex-image>
        </image>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <notation>
      <p>
        Greek letters are often used to measure angles.
        The Greek letters commonly used are <m>\theta</m>,
        <m>\phi</m>, <m>\alpha</m>, <m>\beta</m>, and <m>\gamma</m>.
      </p>
    </notation>
  </introduction>
  <subsection>
    <title>Degree</title>
    <p>
      The <term>measure</term>
          <idx><h>Measure</h></idx>
      of an angle is the amount of rotation from the initial side to the terminal side.
      One unit of measuring angles is the degree.
      One <term>degree</term>
          <idx><h>Degree</h></idx>
      is <m>\frac{1}{360}</m> of a complete revolution,
      so one full revolution is <m>360^{\circ}</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Today we often use decimals to represent the fractional parts of a degree.
      However, fractional parts of a degree were traditionally represented in minutes and seconds.
      One <term>minute</term>
          <idx><h>Minute</h></idx>
      or <em>arc minute</em>,
          <idx><h>Arc Minute</h></idx>
      denoted <m>1'</m>, is defined as
      <m>\frac{1}{60}(1^{\circ})</m> and one <term>second</term>
          <idx><h>Second</h></idx>
      or <em>arc second</em>,
          <idx><h>Arc Second</h></idx>
      denoted <m>1''</m>, is defined as
      <m>\frac{1}{60}(1')</m>. \begin{mybox}[Conversion Between Degree, Minutes,
      and Seconds]
      <md>
        <mrow>1^{\circ}\amp =60' \amp  1'\amp =\left(\frac{1}{60}\right)^{\circ} \amp  1''\amp =\left(\frac{1}{3600}\right)^{\circ}</mrow>
        <mrow>1^{\circ}\amp =3600'' \amp  1'\amp =60'' \amp  1''\amp =\left(\frac{1}{60}\right)'</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>
    <p>
      \end{mybox}
    </p>
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          In the Star Compass
          (<xref ref="fig_star-compass-with-angles">Figure</xref>),
          the angle that divides the houses Manu (northwest) and Noio
          (northwest by west)
          is <m>140.625^{\circ}</m>.
          Represent <m>140.625^{\circ}</m> in degrees, minutes, and seconds.
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="fig_star-compass-with-angles">
          <caption>The Star Compass with the angles indicating the boundaries for each House</caption>
          <image>
<latex-image>
<![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}\draw[<-,dashed] (-1.2cm,0cm) -- (-0.97cm,0cm);
\draw[dashed] (-0.49cm,0cm) -- (0.68cm,0cm);
\draw[->,dashed] (0.98cm,0cm) -- (1.2cm,0cm);
\draw[<-,dashed] (0cm,-1.2cm) -- (0cm,-0.98cm);
\draw[dashed] (0cm,-0.72cm) -- (0cm,0.71cm);
\draw[->,dashed] (0cm,0.98cm) -- (0cm,1.2cm);
\draw[thick] (0cm,0cm) circle(1cm);
\draw[left] (0:0.98) node{\large HIKINA};
\draw[left] (90:0.98) node[rotate=90] {\large `\={A}KAU};
\draw[right] (180:0.98cm) node{\large KOMOHANA};
\draw[left] (270:0.98) node[rotate=-90] {\large HEMA};
\foreach \x in {5.625,16.875,...,90} {
\draw[gray] (0cm,0cm) -- (\x:1cm);
\filldraw[black] (\x:1cm) circle(0.4pt);
\draw (\x:1.2cm) node[rotate=\x] {\(\x^\circ\)};
}
\foreach \x in {95.625,106.875,...,270} {
\draw[gray] (0cm,0cm) -- (\x:1cm);
\filldraw[black] (\x:1cm) circle(0.4pt);
\draw (\x:1.2cm) node[rotate=180+\x] {\(\x^\circ\)};
}
\foreach \x in {275.625,286.875,...,360} {
\draw[gray] (0cm,0cm) -- (\x:1cm);
\filldraw[black] (\x:1cm) circle(0.4pt);
\draw (\x:1.2cm) node[rotate=\x] {\(\x^\circ\)};
}
\foreach \x/\xtext in {
11.25/L\={a},
22.5/`\={A}ina,
33.75/Noio,
45/Manu,
56.25/N\={a}lani,
67.5/N\={a} Leo,
78.75/Haka,
281.25/Haka,
292.5/N\={a} Leo,
303.75/N\={a}lani,
315/Manu,
326.25/Noio,
337.5/`\={A}ina,
348.75/L\={a}
}
\draw[left] (\x:0.98) node[rotate=\x] {\xtext};
\foreach \x/\xtext in {
101.25/Haka,
112.5/N\={a} Leo,
123.75/N\={a}lani,
135/Manu,
146.25/Noio,
157.5/`\={A}ina,
168.75/L\={a},
191.25/L\={a},
202.5/`\={A}ina,
213.75/Noio,
225/Manu,
236.25/N\={a}lani,
247.5/N\={a} Leo,
258.75/Haka
}
\draw[right] (\x:0.98) node[rotate=180+\x] {\xtext};\end{tikzpicture}]]>
</latex-image>
          </image>
        </figure>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          First we will convert <m>0.625^{\circ}</m> to minutes using the conversion <m>1^{\circ}=60'</m>,
          <me>
            0.625^{\circ}=0.625^{\circ}\cdot\frac{60'}{1^{\circ}}=37.5'
          </me>
        </p>
        <p>
          Since <m>1'=60''</m>, we can convert <m>0.5'</m> to seconds:
          <m>\displaystyle 0.5'=0.5'\cdot\frac{60''}{1'}=30''</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          So <m>140.625^{\circ}=140^{\circ}37'30''</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Convert <m>263^{\circ}24'45''</m> to decimal degrees.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          We will first convert <m>24'</m> and <m>45''</m> to degrees.
          <me>
            24'=24\cdot1'=24\cdot\left(\frac{1}{60}\right)^{\circ}=0.4^{\circ}
          </me>
          and
          <me>
            45''=45\cdot1''=45\cdot\left(\frac{1}{3600}\right)^{\circ}=0.0125^{\circ}
          </me>
        </p>
        <p>
          So <m>263^{\circ}24'45''=263^{\circ}+24'+45''=263^{\circ}+0.4^{\circ}+0.0125=263.4125^{\circ}</m>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
    <definition>
      <statement>
        <p>
          If an angle is drawn on the <m>xy</m>-plane and the vertex is at the origin and the initial side is on the positive <m>x</m>-axis,
          then that angle is said to be in
          <term>standard position</term>.
              <idx><h>standard position</h></idx>
          If the angle is measured in a counterclockwise rotation,
          the angle is said to be a <term>positive angle</term>
              <idx><h>positive angle</h></idx>
          and if the angle is measured in a clockwise rotation,
          the angle is said to be a <term>negative angle</term>.
              <idx><h>negative angle</h></idx>
        </p>
        <image>
<latex-image>
<![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}\draw[<->] (-1.25,0)--(1.25,0) node[right]{\(x\)};
\draw[<->] (0,-1.25)--(0,1.25) node[above]{\(y\)};
\filldraw[blue] (1cm,0) circle(1pt);
\filldraw[blue] (60:1.2cm) circle(1pt);
\draw[line width=2pt,blue] (0,0) -- (1,0);
\draw[line width=2pt,blue] (0,0) -- (60:1.2);
\draw[->, line width=1.25pt] (0:0.7cm) arc (0:60:0.7cm) node[midway, right,xshift=0.05cm,yshift=0.2cm] {positive angle};\end{tikzpicture}]]>
</latex-image>
        </image>
        <image>
<latex-image>
<![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}\draw[<->] (-1.25,0)--(1.25,0) node[right]{\(x\)};
\draw[<->] (0,-1.25)--(0,1.25) node[above]{\(y\)};
\filldraw[blue] (1cm,0) circle(1pt);
\filldraw[blue] (-60:1.2cm) circle(1pt);
\draw[line width=2pt,blue] (0,0) -- (1,0);
\draw[line width=2pt,blue] (0,0) -- (-60:1.2);
\draw[->, line width=1.25pt] (0:0.7cm) arc (0:-60:0.7cm) node[midway, right,xshift=0.05cm,yshift=-0.2cm] {negative angle};\end{tikzpicture}]]>
</latex-image>
        </image>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <definition>
      <statement>
        <p>
          When an angle is in standard position,
          the terminal side will either lie in a quadrant or it will lie on the <m>x</m>-axis or <m>y</m>-axis.
          An angle is called a <term>quadrantal angle</term>
              <idx><h>Quadrantal Angle</h></idx>
          if the terminal side lies on <m>x</m>-axis or <m>y</m>-axis.
          The two axes divide the plane into four <term>quadrants</term>.
              <idx><h>Quadrants</h></idx>
          In the Cartesian plane,
          the four quadrants are Quadrant I, II, III, and IV. The corresponding quadrants of Star Compass are Ko`olau (NE), Ho`olua (NW), Kona (SE), and Malanai (SW).
        </p>
        <image>
<latex-image>
<![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}\draw[<->] (-2,0)--(2,0) node[right]{\(x\)};
\draw[<->] (0,-2)--(0,2) node[above]{\(y\)};
\node at (1,1) [ align=center] {I \\ Ko`olau};
\node at (-1,1) [ align=center]{II \\ Ho`olua};
\node at (-1,-1) [ align=center] {III \\ Kona};
\node at (1,-1) [ align=center] {IV \\ Malanai};\end{tikzpicture}]]>
</latex-image>
        </image>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <definition>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <term>Coterminal angles</term>
              <idx><h>Coterminal Angles</h></idx>
          are angles in standard position that have the same initial side and the same terminal side.
          Any angle has infinitely many coterminal angles because each time we add or subtract <m>360^{\circ}</m> from it,
          the resulting angle has the same terminal side.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>90^{\circ}</m> and <m>450^{\circ}</m> are coterminal angles since <m>450^{\circ}-360^{\circ}=90^{\circ}</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <p>
      To determine the quadrant in which an angle lies,
      add or subtract one revolution (<m>360^{\circ}</m>) until you obtain a coterminal angle between
      <m>0^{\circ}</m> ad <m>360^{\circ}</m>.
      The quadrant that the terminal side lies is the quadrant of the angle.
      Quadrantal angles do not lie in any quadrant.
    </p>
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Determine the quadrant in which each angle lies and name the corresponding House and quadrant in the Star Compass
          (<xref ref="fig_star-compass-with-angles">Figure</xref>).
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>140^{\circ}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>-770^{\circ}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>923^{\circ}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Since <m>90^{\circ}\lt 140^{\circ}\lt 180^{\circ}</m>,
                <m>140^{\circ}</m> lies in Quadrant II, or Manu Ho`olua.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Since <m>-770^{\circ}\lt 0</m>,
                we first add <m>3\times360</m> to <m>-770^{\circ}</m> to obtain an angle
                <m>0^{\circ}</m> and <m>360^{\circ}</m>,
                <me>
                  -770^{\circ}+3\times360^{\circ}=310^{\circ}
                </me>
                So <m>310^{\circ}</m> and <m>-770^{\circ}</m> are coterminal.
                Since <m>270^{\circ}\lt 310^{\circ}\lt 360^{\circ}</m>,
                <m>310^{\circ}</m> lies in Quadrant IV, or Manu Malanai.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Since <m>923^{\circ}>360</m> we begin by subtracting <m>2\times360^{\circ}</m>
                <me>
                  923^{\circ}-2\times360^{\circ}=203^{\circ}
                </me>
                So <m>203^{\circ}</m> and <m>923^{\circ }</m> are coterminal.
                Since <m>180^{\circ}\lt 203^{\circ}\lt 270^{\circ}</m>,
                <m>923^{\circ}</m> lies in Quadrant III or `\=Aina Kona.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What is the corresponding quadrant for Nalani Kona?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Locating Nalani Kona in the Star Compass,
          we see it is in Quadrant III.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
    <definition>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A <term>central angle</term>
              <idx><h>Central Angle</h></idx>
          is a positive angle formed at the center of a circle by two radii.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title>Radian</title>
    <p>
      Another way to measure an angle is with <em>radians</em>
      which measure the the arc of a circle that is formed from an angle.
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="core-standards-CCSS_MATH_CONTENT_HSF_TF_A_1">
      <title>Definition of a Radian</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The <term>radian measure</term><idx><h>Radian Measure,
          of angles</h></idx> of a central angle in a circle is the ratio of the length of the arc on a circle subtended by the angle to the radius.
          If <m>r</m> is the radius of the circle,
          <m>\theta</m> is the angle,
          and <m>s</m> is the arc length,
          then we have the following
          <me>
            \theta=\frac{s}{r}
          </me>
        </p>
        <p>
          A radian is abbreviated by <term>rad</term>.
        </p>
        <image>
<latex-image>
<![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}\draw[<->] (-1.25,0)--(1.25,0) node[right]{\(x\)};
\draw[<->] (0,-1.25)--(0,1.25) node[above]{\(y\)};
\draw (0,0) circle (1cm);
\draw[blue] (45:0.95cm) -- (45:1.05cm);
\draw[line width=2pt,blue] (0:1cm) arc (0:45:1cm) node[midway,above,yshift=0.15cm,xshift=0.2cm] {\(s\)};
\filldraw[blue] (1cm,0) circle(1pt);
\filldraw[blue] (45:1cm) circle(1pt);
\draw[line width=2pt,blue] (0,0) -- (1,0) node[midway,below,yshift=-0.1cm]{r};
\draw[line width=2pt,blue] (0,0) -- (45:1);
\draw (0:0.3cm) arc (0:45:0.3cm) node[midway,above,xshift=0.2cm,yshift=-0.1cm]{\(\theta\)};\end{tikzpicture}]]>
</latex-image>
        </image>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
      The measure of a central angle obtained when the length of the arc is also equal to the radius,
      <m>r</m>,
      is called <em>one radian</em> (1 rad).
      Similarly, if <m>\theta=2</m> rad,
      then the arc length equals <m>2r</m>.
    </p>
    <image>
<latex-image>
<![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}\draw[<->] (-1.25,0)--(1.25,0) node[right]{\(x\)};
\draw[<->] (0,-1.25)--(0,1.25) node[above]{\(y\)};
\draw (0,0) circle (1cm);
\draw[blue] (57.3:0.95cm) -- (57.3:1.05cm);
\draw[line width=2pt,blue] (0:1cm) arc (0:57.3:1cm) node[midway,above,yshift=0.15cm,xshift=0.2cm] {\(r\)};
\filldraw[blue] (1cm,0) circle(1pt);
\filldraw[blue] (57.3:1cm) circle(1pt);
\draw[line width=2pt,blue] (0,0) -- (1,0) node[midway,below,yshift=-0.1cm]{r};
\draw[line width=2pt,blue] (0,0) -- (57.3:1);
\draw (0:0.3cm) arc (0:57.3:0.3cm) node[midway,above,xshift=0.2cm,yshift=-0.1cm]{\(\theta\)};\end{tikzpicture}]]>
</latex-image>
    </image>
    <image>
<latex-image>
<![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}\draw[<->] (-1.25,0)--(1.25,0) node[right]{\(x\)};
\draw[<->] (0,-1.25)--(0,1.25) node[above]{\(y\)};
\draw (0,0) circle (1cm);
\draw[blue] (57.3:0.95cm) -- (57.3:1.05cm);
\draw[line width=2pt,blue] (0:1cm) arc (0:57.3:1cm) node[midway,above,yshift=0.15cm,xshift=0.2cm] {\(r\)};
\draw[line width=2pt,blue] (57.3:1cm) arc (57.3:114.6:1cm) node[midway,above,xshift=0.15cm,yshift=0.1cm] {\(r\)};
\filldraw[blue] (1cm,0) circle(1pt);
\filldraw[blue] (57.3:1cm) circle(1pt);
\filldraw[blue] (114.6:1cm) circle(1pt);
\draw[line width=2pt,blue] (0,0) -- (1,0) node[midway,below,yshift=-0.1cm]{r};
\draw[line width=2pt,blue] (0,0) -- (114.6:1);
\draw (0:0.3cm) arc (0:114.6:0.3cm) node[midway,above,xshift=0.2cm,yshift=-0.1cm]{\(\theta\)};\end{tikzpicture}]]>
</latex-image>
    </image>
    <p>
      The circumference of a circle is <m>C=2\pi r</m>.
      This means that the circumference is <m>2\pi\approx6.28</m> times the radius.
      This means that if we were to use a piece of string with the length of the radius,
      we would use six pieces of string plus a fractional piece of the string.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <caption>One rotation of the unit circle is <m>2\pi\approx6.28</m> radians.</caption>
      <image>
<latex-image>
<![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}\draw[<->] (-1.25,0)--(1.25,0) node[right]{\(x\)};
\draw[<->] (0,-1.25)--(0,1.25) node[above]{\(y\)};
\draw (0,0) circle (1cm);
\draw[blue] (57.3:0.95cm) -- (57.3:1.05cm);
\draw[blue] (0:1cm) arc (0:57.3:1cm) node[midway,above,yshift=0.15cm] {\(r\)};
\draw[blue] (57.3:1cm) arc (57.3:114.6:1cm) node[midway,above,xshift=0.15cm] {\(r\)};
\draw[blue] (114.6:1cm) arc (114.6:171.9:1cm) node[midway,above,yshift=0.15cm] {\(r\)};
\draw[blue] (171.9:1cm) arc (171.9:229.2:1cm) node[midway,left] {\(r\)};
\draw[blue] (229.2:1cm) arc (229.2:286.5:1cm) node[midway,below] {\(r\)};
\draw[blue] (286.5:1cm) arc (286.5:343.8:1cm) node[midway,below] {\(r\)};
\filldraw[blue] (1cm,0) circle(1pt) node[black, above right,yshift=0.1cm] {0 radians, \(2\pi\approx6.28\) radians};
\filldraw[blue] (57.3:1cm) circle(1pt) node[black, above right] {1 radian};
\filldraw[blue] (114.6:1cm) circle(1pt) node[black, above left] {2 radians};
\filldraw[blue] (171.9:1cm) circle(1pt) node[black, left] {3 radians};
\filldraw[blue] (229.2:1cm) circle(1pt) node[black, below left] {4 radians};
\filldraw[blue] (286.5:1cm) circle(1pt) node[black, below right] {5 radians};
\filldraw[blue] (343.8:1cm) circle(1pt) node[black, below right] {6 radians};
\node[blue, right] at (1,-0.15) {fractional piece};\end{tikzpicture}]]>
</latex-image>
      </image>
    </figure>
    <p>
      \begin{mybox}[Relationships Between Degrees and Radians] If a circle with radius 1 is drawn,
      there are <m>360^{\circ}</m> and the full arc length is the circumference,
      which is <m>2\pi</m>.
      Therefore, the relationship between degrees and radians is:
      <me>
        360^{\circ}=2\pi \mbox{ radian} , \mbox{or }  180^{\circ}=\pi\mbox{ radian}
      </me>
      <me>
        1\mbox{ radian} =\frac{180^{\circ}}{\pi}
      </me>
      <me>
        1^{\circ}=\frac{\pi}{180}\mbox{ radian}
      </me>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            To convert degree to radians,
            multiply by <m>\dfrac{2\pi\mbox{ radians} }{360^{\circ}}</m> or <m>\dfrac{\pi\mbox{ radian} }{180^{\circ}}</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            To convert radians to degrees,
            multiply by <m>\dfrac{360^{\circ}}{2\pi\mbox{ radians} }</m> or <m>\dfrac{180^{\circ}}{\pi\mbox{ radian} }</m>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
    <p>
      \end{mybox}
    </p>
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Express <m>45^{\circ}</m> in radians.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <m>\displaystyle 45^{\circ}=45^{\circ}\left(\frac{2\pi\mbox{ radians} }{360^{\circ}}\right)=\frac{\pi}{4}\mbox{radians}</m>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Express <m>\dfrac{5\pi}{6}</m> in degrees.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <m>\displaystyle \frac{5\pi}{6}\mbox{rad} =\frac{5\pi}{6}\mbox{rad} \left(\frac{360^{\circ}}{2\pi\mbox{ rad} }\right)=150^{\circ}</m>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
