</latex-image>
        </image>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The measure of the central angle between the two islands is
          <md>
            <mrow>\theta\amp =\amp 21^{\circ}08'-1^{\circ}45'</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp =\amp 19^{\circ}23'</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp =\amp 19^{\circ}+\frac{23}{60}^{\circ}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp \approx\amp 19.3833^{\circ}</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
        <p>
          To find the distance,
          we use <xref ref="thm_arc-length">Theorem</xref> to find the arc length:
          <me>
            s=2\pi r\cdot\left(\frac{\theta}{360^{\circ}}\right)\approx2\pi\cdot(3,960\mbox{ miles} )\frac{19.3833^{\circ}}{360^{\circ}}\approx1,340\mbox{ miles}
          </me>
        </p>
        <p>
          So the distance between Kiritimati and Moloka`i is approximately 1,340 miles.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="core-standards-CCSS_MATH_CONTENT_HSG_C_B_5-c">
    <title>Area of a Sector of a Circle</title>
    <p>
      \begin{mybox}[Area of a Sector]<idx><h>Area</h><h>of sector of circle</h></idx> The area of the sector of a circle of radius <m>r</m> formed by a central angle of <m>\theta</m> is
      <md>
        <mrow>A\amp =\frac{\theta}{360^{\circ}}\cdot\pi\cdot r^2,\mbox{ when \(\theta\) is in degrees}</mrow>
        <mrow>A\amp =\frac{1}{2}r^2\theta,\mbox{ when \(\theta\) is in radians}</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>
    <p>
      \end{mybox} Notice the ratio
      <m>\displaystyle\frac{\theta}{360^{\circ}}</m> is the proportion of the angle <m>\theta</m>
      (in degrees)
      to one complete circle.
      Additionally,
      the circumference of a circle is given by <m>2\pi r</m>.
      Therefore, the arc length is simply the proportion of the central angle to the whole circle multiplied by the circumference of the circle.
      <me>
        s=\mbox{arc length} =\mbox{(proportion of circle)} \cdot\mbox{(circumference)} =\left(\frac{\theta}{360^{\circ}}\right)\cdot(2\pi r)
      </me>
    </p>
    <p>
      Similarly, the area of a circle is given by <m>\pi r^2</m>.
      So the area of sector is the proportion of the central angle to the whole circle multiplied by the area of the circle.
      <me>
        A=\mbox{area of sector} =\mbox{(proportion of circle)} \cdot\mbox{(area of circle)} =\left(\frac{\theta}{360^{\circ}}\right)\cdot\left(\pi r^2\right)
      </me>
    </p>
    <theorem>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Given a circle of radius <m>r</m> formed by a central angle of <m>\theta</m>,
          then the arc length and area of the sector formed by <m>\theta</m> can be expressed as the proportion of the angle to the full circle multiplied by the circumference and area of the circle,
          respectively.
          <me>
            s=\mbox{(proportion of circle)} \cdot\mbox{(circumference)} =\left(\frac{\theta}{360^{\circ}}\right)\cdot(2\pi r)
          </me>
          and
          <me>
            A=\mbox{(proportion of circle)} \cdot\mbox{(area of circle)} =\left(\frac{\theta}{360^{\circ}}\right)\cdot\left(\pi r^2\right)
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          When sailing,
          a wa`a (canoe) cannot make headway by sailing directly into the wind.
          It can only sail beyond <m>67^{\circ}</m> in either direction from the wind
          (<xref ref="fig_Sailing-upwind">Figure</xref>).
          If H&#333;k&#363;le`a sails for 50 miles,
          what is the area of the sector that cannot be sailed?
          Round your answer to the nearest square mile.
        </p>
